sed energy trader, which has been trying to sell the utility for months.=20
Under the deal, Enron is to receive $1.55 billion in cash, $200 million in N=
W Natural preferred stock and $50 million in NW Natural common stock.=20
NW Natural will take over Enron's $75 million balance toward consumer rate c=
uts Enron agreed to when it bought Portland General in 1997.=20
In addition, NW Natural, based in Portland, Ore., will assume about $1.1 bil=
lion in Portland General debt and preferred stock.=20
The common equity stake in NW Natural will give Enron voting rights limited =
to 4.9 percent. Enron, which has agreed to hold its securities in NW Natural=
 for at least 2 1/2 years, also will receive up to two board seats.=20
The deal, subject to regulatory approvals, is expected to close by the fourt=
h quarter of 2002.=20
It's the second time Enron reached a deal to sell Portland General. Nevada-b=
ased Sierra Pacific Resources agreed to buy the utility in November 1999.=20
The deal, valued at about $2 billion plus assumption of $1.1 billion debt an=
d preferred stock, was officially called off in April, although it had been =
considered dead months before.=20
Sierra Pacific planned to sell some of its Nevada assets to raise cash for t=
he deal, but Nevada's move to electricity deregulation was delayed and Sierr=
a couldn't carry out the sales.=20
NW Natural is Oregon's largest natural gas utility, with more than 525,000 c=
ustomers in northwest Oregon and southwest Washington.=20
Portland General serves more than 730,000 customers and owns 2,015 megawatts=
 of electricity generation.=20
Enron is moving away from owning large physical assets so it can focus on tr=
ading and making markets in a variety of commodities.=20
