re not strategic to our wholesale and retail energy business," Ken Lay, Enro=
n's chairman and chief executive, said in a statement.=20
Enron bought the utility in 1997 in a deal worth $2 billion, plus it assumed=
 $1.1 billion in debt and preferred stock.=20
The NW Natural deal represents "a break-even transaction from a gain-loss st=
andpoint," Enron spokeswoman Karen Denne said.=20
Enron could use the proceeds to pay down debt, repurchase stock or invest in=
 the company's high-growth businesses, she said.=20
Enron, when the deal gets closer to completion, must assure investors that t=
he money will be invested in a higher-return opportunity to avoid earnings d=
ilution, said Carol Coale, an analyst with Prudential Securities in Houston.=
=20
Investor confidence in Enron suffered after CEO Jeff Skilling, citing person=
al reasons, unexpectedly resigned in August. Even before then, Enron's stock=
 had come under pressure for a variety of reasons.=20
